{
  "texts": [
    "The ⊑-forth property follows from the stronger property in Fact 4.9.2.For ⊑-back, suppose y ′ ⊑ ′ h(x), so y ′ ∈ ↓ ′ h(x).",
    "Since F ′ is separative and full, ↓ ′ y ′ ∈ P ′ by Fact 4.6.1.",
    "Then by the ⊑-matching condition of possibility morphisms,↓ ′ h(x) ∩ ↓ ′ y ′ ̸ = ∅ implies ↓x ∩ h -1 [↓ ′ y ′] ̸ = ∅,so there is a y ⊑ x such that h(y) ⊑ ′ y ′, which establishes ⊑-back.For R-forth, since F ′ is strong and full, R ′ i (h(x)) ∈ P ′ by Proposition 2.35.",
    "Then by the pull back property of possibility morphisms, h -1 [R ′ i (h(x))] ∈ P, so by the left-to-right direction of the R-matching property of possibility morphisms,R ′ i (h(x)) ⊆ R ′ i (h(x)) implies R i (x) ⊆ h -1 [R ′ i (h(x))], which is equivalent to the R-forth condition that xR i y implies h(x)R ′ i h(y).",
    "Finally, for R-back, suppose h(x)R ′ i y ′ and z ′ ⊑ y ′."
  ]
}